    <section id="about">
        <h2>About Me</h2>
        <p>I am a Ph.D. candidate with a unique focus that bridges chemical engineering and mathematics. My research interests include the application of modular forms, Ricci flow, and number theory in optimization and complex systems.</p>
        <p>Recently, I had the opportunity to present my work at the AIChE annual meeting, where I engaged in discussions with distinguished academics, such as Professor Ali Elkamel.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="research">
        <h2>Research Projects</h2>
        <h3>1. Modular Forms in Combinatorial Optimization</h3>
        <p>This project explores how modular forms can be applied to solve complex combinatorial problems, including the Asymmetric Traveling Salesman Problem (ATSP). The approach involves deep number-theoretic concepts integrated into optimization strategies.</p>

        <h3>2. Stochastic Optimization Using Ricci Flow</h3>
        <p>In this work, I investigate the application of Ricci flow and inverse Ricci flow for optimizing non-convex functions. This cross-disciplinary research connects differential geometry with practical optimization techniques.</p>

        <h3>3. The Superposition Principle and the Riemann Hypothesis</h3>
        <p>This ambitious project introduces a new function, <em>G(s)</em>, leveraging wave superposition to study the distribution of zeros of the Riemann zeta function. The work aims to provide a fresh perspective on one of mathematics' greatest unsolved problems.</p>
    </section>

